### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

I am trying to build a type-safe API for dynamically rendering components with `NgComponentOutlet` and passing inputs through `ngComponentOutletInputs`.

A simplified version looks like this:

```ts
import { Type, InputSignal } from '@angular/core';

function provideSomeComponent(
  component: Type<{ foo: InputSignal<string> }>,
) {
  return { provide: SOME_COMPONENT_TOKEN, useValue: component };
}
```

This works as long as the component input binding name is the same as the class property name:

```ts
@Component({
  standalone: true,
  template: `{{ foo() }}`,
})
class SomeComponent {
  foo = input.required<string>();
}

provideSomeComponent(SomeComponent);
```

However, the type-level contract becomes unsound when the input has an alias:

```ts
@Component({
  standalone: true,
  template: `{{ foo() }}`,
})
class SomeComponent {
  foo = input.required<string>({ alias: 'bar' });
}

provideSomeComponent(SomeComponent); // TypeScript accepts this
```

The component satisfies the TypeScript contract:

```ts
Type<{ foo: InputSignal<string> }>
```

But at runtime the public input binding name is `bar`, not `foo`.

So when this is later passed to `NgComponentOutlet`:

```html
<ng-container
  *ngComponentOutlet="
    provided.component;
    inputs: {foo: ...}
  "
/>
```

Angular tries to bind `foo`, while the actual public input name is `bar`.

This means that TypeScript says the contract is valid, but Angular runtime input binding does not match the same contract.


### Proposed solution

### Proposed solution

Angular could expose a public type-level or runtime-assisted API for deriving the public input contract of a component.

For example, conceptually:

```ts
type ComponentWithInputs<{
  foo: string;
}>;
```

So, this type should accept any components, that inputs contract is satisfies:

```ts
class SomeComponent1 {
  bar = input.required<string>({ alias: 'foo' });
}

class SomeComponent2 {
  foo = input.required<string>();
}

class SomeComponent3 {
  foo = input.required<string>({ alias: 'bar' });
}

function provideSomeComponent(
  component: Type<ComponentWithInputs<{
    foo: string;
  }>>,
) {
  return { provide: SOME_COMPONENT_TOKEN, useValue: component };
}

provideSomeComponent(SomeComponent1) // ok
provideSomeComponent(SomeComponent2) // ok
provideSomeComponent(SomeComponent3) // error
```

### Why this matters

This is especially problematic for libraries that want to provide type-safe APIs around dynamic component rendering, dialogs, portals, overlays, routed component inputs, or CMS-driven component outlets.

### Alternatives considered

A library can require users to manually provide the alias map:

```ts
provideSomeComponent(SomeComponent, {
  inputAliases: {
    foo: 'bar',
  },
});
```

But this duplicates Angular metadata and can drift from the actual component declaration.

A library can also ban input aliases for dynamically rendered components, but that is restrictive and hard to enforce globally.

